>[Question]
>In maths, there have been several theorems that have only been 
proven hundreds of years after first being stated, Fermat's Last 
Theorem being an obvious example. Sometimes, a theorem can be tested 
for very large numbers of cases, such that one could say 'we're 
almost certain this is true'. I was just wondering if there has ever 
been a case were something that has been 'pretty much' proven like 
this has later turned out not to be true, and whether theorems 
relying on that assumption have had to be discarded... or whether 
there is a point where you just say 'lets call it proven' and start 
using it to work on other things?
>
